{{Quote|Yes, it's a story my ''father'' told me, of something that happened to Ben ''years'' ago-- back in the days of the old ''Republic''...|Leia Organa|<ref name="Star Wars (1977) 24">[[Star Wars (1977) 24|''Star Wars'' (1977) 24]]</ref>}}
'''''Star Wars 24: Silent Drifting''''' is the twenty-fourth issue in the [[Star Wars (1977)|Marvel ''Star Wars'']] series of comics.

==Plot summary==
After [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] skillfully pilots the [[Millennium Falcon/Legends|''Millennium Falcon'']] to destroy two [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE fighters]], [[Princess/Legends|Princess]] [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia]] mentions that [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] pilots developed that same maneuver. She recounts one particular event involving [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]].

Kenobi, traveling as a passenger on a [[pleasure cruiser]], is notified by [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Quasar (Human)|Quasar]] that [[Merson pirates/Legends|Merson pirates]] have been spotted in the [[Merson asteroid belt]]. The attacking ships are quickly destroyed, but Obi-Wan suspects the [[Mersons]] to have been lured by a signal from within the cruiser. The other passengers immediately accuse [[Augustus Tryll]], a known criminal, of working with the Mersons, but Kenobi is not as quick to judge without proof. When more Merson ships are spotted, he realizes that the signal the pirates are tracking is originating from an innocent fermentation device on board the cruiser. Once he destroys this device, the Merson ships lose track of the pleasure cruiser, and danger is avoided.

==Development==
This is [[Mary Jo Duffy]]'s first ''[[Star Wars]]'' issue. She would later be the regular writer on the title beginning with [[Star Wars (1977) 70|''Star Wars'' (1977) 70]].

==Continuity==
The framing story takes place after the events of [[Star Wars (1977) 15|''Star Wars'' (1977) 15]], according to the notation on the first page. Aside from the first four pages and the last half page, the entire story in this issue is a flashback to a time when Obi-Wan Kenobi was an active [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] in the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]]. This is the first published story to take place in the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] era.

One of the letters in this issue's letters page criticizes the comic series for making [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke]] and Leia "... act more like young brother and sister than sweethearts." Although the creators of the book didn't know this at the time, four years later [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']] would reveal that they were indeed siblings.

The characterization of Obi-Wan Kenobi is rather inconsistent to how he's characterized in the prequels and A New Hope, as he's portrayed as more brash and not unwilling to kill regular people who attack him over merely dismembering them.

